# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] The Brooklyn baseball club was formed in 1883 by real estate magnate and baseball enthusiast Charles Byrne who convinced his brother-in-law Joseph Doyle and casino operator Ferdinand Abell to start the team with him.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] Byrne set up a grandstand on fifth avenue and named it Washington Park in honor of George Washington.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] The team played in the minor Inter-State Association of Professional Baseball Clubs.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] Doyle became the first manager of the team, which drew 6,000 fans to its first home game on May 12, 1883, against the Trenton team.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] (This was actually the second game the club played in Brooklyn; three days earlier, with Washington Park not yet ready, the Greys beat Harrisburg 7–1 at the Parade Ground.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] It was the only professional match ever held at the ground, with some 2,000 fans in attendance.) The team won the league title after the **Camden Merritt** club disbanded on July 20 and Brooklyn picked up some of its better players.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] The Grays were invited to join the American Association for the following season.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season] The **1884 Brooklyn Atlantics season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season] It was the first season in the American Association for the team, and they finished the year in ninth place.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season] The Brooklyn baseball team had played as the **Brooklyn Grays** in the Interstate Association in 1883, where they won the championship.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season] In 1884, Charles Byrne moved the team into the American Association, renaming them the Atlantics in tribute to the old National Association Brooklyn Atlantics team.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The **1884 major league baseball season** began on April 17, 1884.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The National League and American Association's regular seasons ended on October 15, with the Providence Grays and New York Metropolitans as the NL and AA pennant winners, respectively.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The newly founded Union Association regular season ended on October 19, with the St.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason between the AA and NL began with Game 1 of the first World's Championship Series (the first inter-league championship game of its kind in the Major Leagues) on October 23 and ended with Game 3 on October 25, in what was a best-of-five-playoff.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Grays swept the Metropolitans in three games, capturing their first World's Championship Series.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the 1884 season, in September 1883, the Union Association was formed, in direct contravention to the reserve rule (that a ballplayer could be reserved by a team) of the 1883 National Agreement (a.k.a.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Tripartite Agreement) signed between the National League, American Association, and minor league Northwestern League.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] In response to formation of the UA, the AA expanded their league from an eight teams to twelve teams to undermine the weak footing the UA had, as UA teams were mostly in cities that already had established AA and NL teams.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The latter played their last game on August 2, and were replaced by the minor league Eastern League's Richmond Virginians to finish Washington's schedule.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Union Association was largely unstable throughout its only year in existence (though confidence in the league remained high), as three of its founding teams would not make it to the end of the season.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Altoona Mountain Citys folded on May 31, and were replaced by the Kansas City Cowboys on June 7.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Keystones folded on August 7, and were replaced by the Eastern League's Wilmington Quicksteps.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Browns relocated to Pittsburgh as the Pittsburgh Stogies following their August 21 game.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Quicksteps would fold on September 15, while the Stogies would fold just three days later.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] On September 27, the Milwaukee Brewers and St.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Paul Saints) were recruited from the Northwestern League to finish the Philadelphia / Wilmington and Chicago/Pittsburgh schedules, respectively.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The 1884 season featured the second African American player in the major leagues (following William Edward White five years prior), debuting May 1 and playing 42 games for the Toledo Blue Stockings of the American Association.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] During his tenure, he faced abuse from other players (including teammates), fans, and the press, and even threats of being mobbed by 75 men before a road trip to Richmond, Virginia, before being released due to injury on September 29, prior to the road trip.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] His brother Weldy Walker played on the Toledo Blue Stockings for five games between July and August, becoming the third African American in the major leagues.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The 1884 schedule consisted of 110 games for all teams in the American Association, which had twelve active teams, and 112 games for all teams in the National League and Union Association, each of which had eight active teams.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Each AA team was scheduled to play 10 games against the other eleven teams in their league, and each of NL & UA teams were scheduled to play 16 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The National League increased its total games per team from 98 to 112, 14 games to 16 games per seven opponents.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The new Union Association copied this format.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the American Association, expanding from eight to twelve teams, changed from the 98-game format to the 110-game format.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would continue to use their 112-game format through the following season, while the American Association would copy the NL format.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Union Association Opening Day took place on April 17 featuring six teams, while American Association and National League Opening Days took place on May 1, featuring all twelve and all eight teams, respectively.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Union Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 19 featuring four teams, while the American Association and National League would see their final day of the regular season on October 15 featuring all twelve teams and four teams, respectively.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The 1884 World's Championship Series took place between October 23 and October 25.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Four teams played in four neutral or alternate sites in which they were treated as the home team.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] 35 tie games (19 in AA, 10 in NL, 6 in UA), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in *italics* indicates a team a player was on from a different league.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Any stat from said different league is not calculated to determine the league leader.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Four of these teams folded, one of which relocated cities prior to folding.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Indianapolis Hoosiers hosted 11 Sunday games at the Bruce Grounds north of Indianapolis city limits in Center Township on May 18, 25, June 22, 29, July 6, 13, 20, August 3, 10, 31, and September 21.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1885-brooklyn-grays-season] The **1885 Brooklyn Grays** finished the season in fifth place.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1885-brooklyn-grays-season] The team added several players from the defunct Cleveland Blues team after team owner Charlie Byrne bought the Blues assets for $10,000 after the 1884 season.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1886-brooklyn-grays-season] The **1886 Brooklyn Grays season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1886-brooklyn-grays-season] The team finished the season in third place with a record of 76–61 (their first winning season), 16 games behind the St.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1887-brooklyn-grays-season] The **1887 Brooklyn Grays** finished the season in sixth place.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1888-brooklyn-bridegrooms-season] With the 1888 season, the Brooklyn Grays underwent a name change to the **Brooklyn Bridegrooms**, a nickname that resulted from several team members getting married around the same time.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1888-brooklyn-bridegrooms-season] Also, owner Charles Byrne decided to withdraw from managing the team's on field activities and turned the reins over to more experienced baseball manager Bill McGunnigle.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/1888-brooklyn-bridegrooms-season] That, along with the Bridegrooms' purchase of several top players from the defunct New York Metropolitans, led to a dramatic on field improvement as the team finished in second place in the American Association.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season] The **2002 Los Angeles Dodgers season** was the 113th for the franchise in Major League Baseball, and their 45th season in Los Angeles, California.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season] The season saw Dan Evans take over as General Manager and in his first season the team won 92 games and was not eliminated from post season contention until the next-to-last day of the season, finishing third overall in the National League West.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season] Shawn Green hit 42 home runs to become the first Los Angeles Dodger to have back-to-back 40 or more homer seasons (Duke Snider had four consecutive 40+ homer seasons when the team was in Brooklyn).
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season] He had four homers in one game on May 23 against the Milwaukee Brewers.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season] He went 6-for-6 in that game and set a Major League mark for total bases with 19.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season] The number broke the previous record of 18 total bases set by Joe Adcock. Éric Gagné, a former starter, was turned into the closer and proceeded to set a club record for saves with 52.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season] This is also their first season to be broadcast on KCOP (13).
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season] The Dodgers selected 52 players in this draft.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season] Of those, nine of them would eventually play Major League baseball.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season] They gained a supplemental first round pick and an extra second round pick as compensation for losing pitcher Chan Ho Park to the Texas Rangers as a free agent.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season] With their first round pick, the Dodgers selected first baseman James Loney from Lawrence E Elkins High School in Missouri City, Texas.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season] Loney would make it to the Majors in 2006 and was the Dodgers primary starting first baseman until he was traded in 2012.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season] He hit 71 home runs and drove in 451 RBI in his seven seasons with the Dodgers, while hitting .284.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season] The supplemental first round pick was left handed pitcher Greg Miller from Esperanza High School in Anaheim, California.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season] Miller was a highly touted prospect and the 2003 Dodgers minor league pitcher of the year after he went 11–4 with a 2.49 ERA in 21 starts for the Vero Beach Dodgers.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season] However, he missed the entire 2004 season with an arm injury and was never able to regain his touch.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season] In eight minor league seasons (the last in the independent American Association) he was 24–15 with a 3.89 ERA in 221 games (53 starts).
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season] This was a fairly successful draft, after several sub-par drafts that proceeded it.
[src:2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season/2002-los-angeles-dodgers-season] Also drafted this season were relief pitcher Jonathan Broxton (second round), starting pitchers James McDonald (11th round, drafted as a first baseman) and Eric Stults (15th round) and catcher Russell Martin (17th round, drafted as a second baseman).
